\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 I appreciate the gut-check. You are entirely right to be cautious\'97when a physicist of Dave\'92s caliber spends two full days digging into your data, any counter-argument needs to be airtight, grounded in fundamental materials physics, and free of hand-waving.\
To answer your question directly: 
\f1\b \cf2 \strokec2 I am highly confident in the rebuttal points, specifically because your experimental design inadvertently built a beautiful trap for Dave's thermal creep hypothesis.
\f0\b0 \cf2 \strokec2 \
Dave is doing exactly what a top-tier experimentalist should do\'97looking for an elegant, single-variable explanation (Occam's razor) that resolves an apparent conflict between your data and naive theoretical calculations. But the physical properties of the specific magnet grades you chose to test make his thermal aging hypothesis highly improbable.\
Here is why the physics stands firm, framed in a way that respects Dave\'92s insight while holding the line on the data.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf2 1. Why the Materials Physics Binds the Argument\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf2 Dave\'92s core idea is that the $-0.2\\%$ drop is short-term thermal annealing (creep), accelerated by the tunnel's higher ambient temperatures ($29^\\circ\\text\{C\}$ to $45^\\circ\\text\{C\}$).\
If you are going to push back on this, the 
\f1\b \cf2 \strokec2 Dysprosium Inversion
\f0\b0 \cf2 \strokec2  is your anchor. Here is the rigorous breakdown of why:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Mechanics of Creep:
\f0\b0  Thermal creep occurs when thermal fluctuations help magnetic domains overcome the intrinsic coercivity energy barrier ($H_\{cj\}$) to flip prematurely.\
\ls6\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Material Specs:
\f0\b0  Your N52SH magnets have an intrinsic coercivity rating meant to withstand temperatures up to $150^\\circ\\text\{C\}$. Your N42EH magnets are heavily doped with Dysprosium (Dy) specifically to increase their anisotropy field and boost coercivity, rating them up to $200^\\circ\\text\{C\}$.\
\ls6\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Thermal Expectation:
\f0\b0  At tunnel temperatures of $45^\\circ\\text\{C\}$, both magnets are well below their ratings, but N52SH is objectively closer to its limit. If Dave's hypothesis were correct, the N52SH grade should show noticeably 
\f2\i more
\f0\i0  thermal creep than the ruggedized N42EH.\
\ls6\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Reality:
\f0\b0  Your data shows the exact opposite. The thermally superior, Dy-doped N42EH degraded 
\f2\i more
\f0\i0 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf2 The Physics Conclusion:
\f0\b0  A purely thermal mechanism cannot explain why a material engineered specifically to resist thermal demagnetization performed worse than a less-stable grade at identical temperatures. It requires a radiation-driven explanation\'97namely, the massive thermal neutron capture cross-section of Dysprosium ($^\{164\}\\text\{Dy\}$ is $\\sim 2600$ barns) localized right at the critical grain boundaries.\cf2 \strokec2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf2 2. De-coupling the Spatial Profiles\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf2 Dave notes a great correlation: the arcs have copper coils, copper coils dissipate $I^2R$ heat, the arcs are hotter, and your magnets in the arcs degraded. It\'92s a compelling narrative.\
However, your note tracks two distinct radiation vectors: 
\f1\b \cf2 \strokec2 neutrons
\f0\b0 \cf2 \strokec2  and 
\f1\b \cf2 \strokec2 gammas
\f0\b0 \cf2 \strokec2 .\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
