\f0\b0\fs24 \cf2 The previous model used your correlation coefficient ($\\rho = 0.389$) to calculate an $R^2 \\approx 0.15$, arguing that neutron dose only explains 15% of the variance, and effectively handing the remaining 85% to Dave's thermal hypothesis. That is a dangerous misapplication of statistics in accelerator physics.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls25\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Accelerator dosimetry is notoriously imprecise, often carrying massive systematic error bars due to spatial tracking limits and saturation.\
\ls25\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Furthermore, radiation damage in permanent magnets is highly non-linear, often depending on specific neutron energy spectra (e.g., thermal vs. fast) rather than just total integrated dose.\
\ls25\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 A weak linear correlation in this context is almost certainly an artifact of dosimetry resolution, not proof that radiation is a minor variable.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf2 \strokec2 4. The Dysprosium Inversion Holds the Line\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf2 This remains your indisputable trump card. If the degradation were driven by ambient thermal creep (whether from a 45\'b0C tunnel or a 25\'b0C linac), the thermally superior, Dy-doped 
